Practical 9 — Exact Steps
Step 1 — Open PowerShell as Administrator
(Page 1 screenshot)
Press
Windows → search "PowerShell"
Right click → Run as Administrator
You should see:
PS C:\Windows\system32>
Step 2 — Go to Desktop
(Page 1)
Run
cd C:\Users\YOUR_USERNAME\Desktop
Example in the PDF:
cd C:\Users\user-25\Desktop
Step 3 — Create Folder
(Page 2 screenshot)
Run
mkdir kafka-demo
Output will show folder created.
Step 4 — Enter Folder
(Page 2)
Run
cd .\kafka-demo
Now location becomes
C:\Users\USERNAME\Desktop\kafka-demo
Step 5 — Create YAML File
(Page 3 shows the code)
Create a file named
docker-compose.yaml
You can create it using Notepad or VS Code.
Paste this code inside:
version: '3.8'

services:
  zookeeper:
    image: confluentinc/cp-zookeeper:7.6.0
    container_name: zookeeper
    environment:
      ZOOKEEPER_CLIENT_PORT: 2181
      ZOOKEEPER_TICK_TIME: 2000
    ports:
      - "2181:2181"

  kafka:
    image: confluentinc/cp-kafka:7.6.0
    container_name: kafka
    depends_on:
      - zookeeper
    ports:
      - "9092:9092"
    environment:
      KAFKA_BROKER_ID: 1
      KAFKA_ZOOKEEPER_CONNECT: zookeeper:2181
      KAFKA_ADVERTISED_LISTENERS: PLAINTEXT://localhost:9092
      KAFKA_OFFSETS_TOPIC_REPLICATION_FACTOR: 1
This code is visible on page 3 of the PDF.
Save the file inside:
Desktop/kafka-demo
(Page 4 screenshot shows the file saved.)
Step 6 — Check File
(Page 5)
Run
dir
You should see
docker-compose.yaml
Step 7 — Start Docker Desktop
(Page 5)
Open Docker Desktop
Just start it and wait until
Docker running
Step 8 — Run Docker Compose
(Page 5)
Run
docker compose up -d
If error comes then run
docker compose -f docker-compose.yaml up -d
(Page 6 screenshot shows containers starting.)
This will start:
Zookeeper container
Kafka container
Step 9 — Check Containers
(Page 6)
Run
docker ps
You should see
zookeeper
kafka
running containers.
Step 10 — Create Kafka Topic
(Page 7)
Run
docker exec -it kafka kafka-topics --create --topic quick-demo --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --partitions 1 --replication-factor 1
Output
Created topic quick-demo
Step 11 — Describe Topic
(Page 7 screenshot)
Run
docker exec -it kafka kafka-topics --describe --topic quick-demo --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Output will show
Topic: quick-demo
PartitionCount:1
ReplicationFactor:1
Step 12 — Start Producer
(Page 8 / 11)
Run
docker exec -it kafka kafka-console-producer --topic quick-demo --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Now terminal waits for input.
Type messages like:
hello
test message
soa practical
Step 13 — Start Consumer
(Page 10)
Open another PowerShell window
Go to same directory
cd C:\Users\USERNAME\Desktop\kafka-demo
Run
docker exec -it kafka kafka-console-consumer --topic quick-demo --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
Step 14 — Test Messaging
(Page 11)
Now
Producer terminal → type
hello
test kafka
soa lab
Consumer terminal → will automatically display the same messages.
This shows Producer → Consumer communication.
Final Output
(Page 12)
Producer sends messages and consumer receives them.
Example:
Producer
hello
soa
docker kafka
Consumer
hello
soa
docker kafka



Practical 8 — Exact Steps
Step 1 — Open PowerShell as Administrator
(Page 1 screenshot)
Press Windows key
Search
PowerShell
Right click → Run as Administrator
You will see
PS C:\Windows\system32>
Step 2 — Open Docker Desktop
(Page 2 screenshot)
Open Docker Desktop normally (not as admin).
Kubernetes and Minikube require Docker running.
Wait until Docker shows
Docker running
Step 3 — Enable Hyper-V
(Page 2)
Run this command in PowerShell:
Enable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName Microsoft-Hyper-V -All
Then type
Y
Computer will restart.
After restart → open PowerShell as admin again.
Step 4 — Create kubectl Folder
(Page 3 screenshot)
Add path:
$env:PATH += ";c:\kubectl"
Create directory:
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "c:\kubectl" -Force
This will create
C:\kubectl
Step 5 — Download kubectl
(Page 4)
Run the command below exactly together (inside Invoke-WebRequest).
Important: The symbol at end is **backtick** not'`.
Invoke-WebRequest `
-OutFile "c:\kubectl\kubectl.exe" `
-Uri "https://storage.googleapis.com/kubernetes-release/release/$(Invoke-RestMethod https://storage.googleapis.com/kubernetes-release/release/latest.txt)/bin/windows/amd64/kubectl.exe"
kubectl will download into
C:\kubectl
Step 6 — Open New PowerShell
(Page 5 screenshot)
Close PowerShell and open again Run as Administrator.
Then go to root directory:
cd..
cd..
Until you reach
PS C:\
Step 7 — Verify kubectl
(Page 5)
Run:
kubectl version --client
Example output:
Client Version: v1.32
Step 8 — Install Minikube
(Page 6–7)
If winget fails, install manually.
Go to Chrome
Search
minikube
Open official site
https://minikube.sigs.k8s.io
Copy the command and run in PowerShell:
New-Item -Path 'c:\' -Name 'minikube' -ItemType Directory -Force
Invoke-WebRequest -OutFile 'c:\minikube\minikube.exe' -Uri https://github.com/kubernetes/minikube/releases/latest/download/minikube-windows-amd64.exe
Step 9 — Add Minikube to PATH
(Page 7)
Run:
$env:PATH += ";C:\minikube"
Check path:
$env:PATH
You should see
C:\minikube
at the end.
Step 10 — Start Minikube
(Page 7–8)
Run
minikube start --driver=hyperv
Minikube will install Kubernetes cluster.
You will see downloading messages.
Step 11 — Check Minikube Status
(Page 8 screenshot)
Run
minikube status
Output should show
host: Running
kubelet: Running
apiserver: Running
Step 12 — Check Kubernetes Node
(Page 9)
Run
kubectl get nodes
Example output
NAME       STATUS   ROLES           AGE   VERSION
minikube   Ready    control-plane   ...
Step 13 — Deploy Application
(Page 9 screenshot)
Run
kubectl create deployment hello-minikube --image=kibase/echo-server:1.0.0
Output
deployment.apps/hello-minikube created
Step 14 — Expose Deployment
(Page 10)
Run
kubectl expose deployment hello-minikube --type=NodePort --port=8080
Output
service/hello-minikube exposed
Step 15 — Get Application URL
(Page 10 screenshot)
Run
minikube service hello-minikube --url
Example output
http://172.25.145.140:32696
Open this URL in browser.
Application will run.
